# Ai-chatbot-for-college-notes-using-LLM-Retrieval-Augmented-Generation-RAG-


This project titled “AI Chatbot for College Notes using LLM and Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)” is structured in a modular repository so that each part of the system has a clearly defined responsibility. The repository is designed to separate data, intelligence, backend communication, and user interaction, which makes the system easier to understand, maintain, and scale in an academic as well as real-world environment.

At the root level of the repository lies the main project folder, which acts as the central container for all components. This root directory does not contain logic itself but organizes the project into meaningful subdirectories. Such a structure ensures that changes in one part of the system, such as updating notes or modifying the user interface, do not affect the core intelligence of the chatbot.

The data directory is responsible for holding the raw academic content. Inside it, the docs subdirectory stores all college notes in PDF format. These PDFs may include lecture notes, scanned handwritten notes, or presentation slides converted into documents. The system reads these files using a PDF loader, conceptually similar to calling PyPDFLoader("data/docs/subject_notes.pdf"). Keeping notes in a separate folder allows students or teachers to update or add new material without touching any part of the codebase.

Once the notes are available, the embeddings directory comes into play. This directory represents the long-term memory of the chatbot. Inside it, the faiss_index subfolder stores the vector representations of the notes. These vectors are numerical encodings of the text that capture semantic meaning. After the notes are processed, they are saved locally using a mechanism similar to FAISS.save_local("embeddings/faiss_index"). This design ensures that the system does not need to reprocess the notes every time the chatbot starts, which significantly improves performance and efficiency.

The core intelligence of the chatbot resides inside the app directory. This directory contains all the logic that transforms notes into knowledge and enables intelligent question answering. The first important file in this directory is ingest.py. This file is responsible for converting static PDF notes into a searchable knowledge base. It loads the PDFs, splits the text into smaller overlapping chunks using logic such as RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter(chunk_size=1000, chunk_overlap=200), and then converts these chunks into embeddings. The overlap between chunks ensures that important contextual information is not lost, which is especially important for academic explanations where definitions and examples may span multiple paragraphs. The output of this process is stored in the FAISS vector database inside the embeddings directory.

After ingestion, the rag_chain.py file handles the reasoning process. This file connects the vector database with the language model. When a student asks a question, the system retrieves the most relevant chunks from the FAISS index using a retriever mechanism conceptually expressed as db.as_retriever(k=3). This means that only the top three most relevant sections of the notes are selected. These retrieved sections are then passed to the language model, configured with deterministic settings such as ChatOpenAI(temperature=0), to generate an accurate and syllabus-aligned response. This file is the heart of the Retrieval-Augmented Generation approach, as it ensures that the language model answers questions strictly based on the student’s notes rather than general internet knowledge.

The api.py file serves as the communication layer of the system. It exposes the chatbot functionality through a backend API built using FastAPI. When a user sends a question through an endpoint such as /chat, the API receives the input, forwards it to the RAG chain, and returns the generated answer. Conceptually, this interaction resembles sending a request like { "question": "Explain Ohm’s Law" } and receiving a structured response. This API-based design allows the chatbot to be easily integrated with different frontends or even external systems like a college learning management system.

The user interaction layer is implemented inside the ui directory, which contains the Streamlit application. This part of the repository focuses entirely on user experience and does not contain any AI logic. The Streamlit interface provides a simple text input where students can type their questions, similar to st.text_input("Ask your notes"), and view the answers returned by the backend. This separation ensures that changes to the interface do not affect the reasoning or retrieval mechanisms.

Configuration and environment management are handled through the .env file, which securely stores sensitive information such as API keys. This approach prevents hardcoding secrets into the code and keeps the repository safe for public platforms like GitHub. Dependency management is handled by the requirements.txt file, which lists all the libraries needed to run the project. This ensures that anyone cloning the repository can reproduce the same environment using a single installation command.

Finally, the .gitignore file ensures that sensitive files, generated embeddings, and cache data are not uploaded to version control. The README.md file provides a human-readable explanation of the project, guiding users and evaluators on how the system works and how it can be executed.

Overall, each subsection of the repository contributes to a clear and logical workflow. The data folder stores the academic content, the ingestion process converts that content into embeddings, the reasoning layer retrieves and interprets relevant information, the API layer manages communication, and the user interface allows students to interact with the system. Together, these components form a robust and exam-oriented AI chatbot that delivers accurate, context-aware answers directly from college notes using Retrieval-Augmented Generation.
